In order to guide a further optimization of the nanohole arrays in our solar cells, we performed optical simulations by using an RCWA method and the results are illustrated in Fig. 6. The fractional area of the nanoholes at the surface of the Si wafer is fixed at 80% for all the calculations, and an antireflection layer with a refractive index of 1.9 is assumed to be coated over the nanoholes. The periodic Si nanostructures provide multiple effects of graded index and grating diffraction for effective light managements35. The average weighted-reflectances were calculated depending on the period and depth of the nanohole arrays and presented in Fig. 6(a). The weighted reflectance (Rw) is calculated by averaging the reflectance (R) over a wavelength range from 350 nm to 1200 nm with a weighting of a standard solar irradiation of AM 1.5 G (I).1RW=∫350nm1200nmR(λ)I(λ)dλ∫350nm1200nmI(λ)dλ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
